25
00:01:13,551 --> 00:01:15,092
So what is a schema?

26
00:01:15,132 --> 00:01:16,512
This is a good place for us to start.

27
00:01:16,893 --> 00:01:19,655
And one example of this is obviously what you see here.

28
00:01:20,215 --> 00:01:21,577
this cute little puppy dog.

29
00:01:22,018 --> 00:01:24,161
And in research, a schema is defined

30
00:01:24,382 --> 00:01:27,587
as an organized mental structure or representation of stimuli.

31
00:01:27,967 --> 00:01:31,392
And schemas really do work to streamline our information

32
00:01:31,433 --> 00:01:33,976
processing and categorize objects to help

33
00:01:34,037 --> 00:01:35,118
them relate to one another.

34
00:01:35,984 --> 00:01:40,185
General categorizations like this can more or less be considered universal.

35
00:01:40,325 --> 00:01:42,626
This is a picture of a dog, not of an airplane,

36
00:01:43,087 --> 00:01:45,247
and schemas tend to reside in our long-term memory.

37
00:01:45,708 --> 00:01:50,109
That said, one more complicated aspect of schemas is their subjective nature.

38
00:01:50,350 --> 00:01:52,570
So if I had everyone in the audience close their eyes

39
00:01:52,671 --> 00:01:54,871
and imagine the concept of a dog,

40
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:57,172
we would see a lot of variety in this room.

41
00:01:57,292 --> 00:01:58,653
I might picture a German shepherd,

42
00:01:58,693 --> 00:02:01,094
and you might think of Snoopy or something like that.

43
00:02:01,845 --> 00:02:03,886
So in terms of looking at schemas in action,

44
00:02:04,047 --> 00:02:06,969
what we can see here is that when we first learn,

45
00:02:07,049 --> 00:02:09,191
often when we're young, what a dog is,

46
00:02:09,211 --> 00:02:11,573
a schema is formed, and this is called assimilation.

47
00:02:12,133 --> 00:02:13,995
And this is the process of fitting information

48
00:02:14,095 --> 00:02:16,216
that contains the features we associate

49
00:02:16,497 --> 00:02:18,318
that defines this stimulus.

50
00:02:18,698 --> 00:02:21,581
So for example, a dog typically has two ears, a tail,

51
00:02:21,861 --> 00:02:23,702
four legs, and tends to bark.

52
00:02:24,443 --> 00:02:27,065
And when we are out and about in the real world,

53
00:02:27,345 --> 00:02:28,967
we see these stimuli.

54
00:02:29,890 --> 00:02:33,031
And we carry forward what we've assimilated in long-term memory with us.

55
00:02:33,331 --> 00:02:35,712
Is this a dog? Does it match the known criteria?

56
00:02:36,052 --> 00:02:37,333
In this case, the answer would be yes.

57
00:02:37,893 --> 00:02:41,475
So over time, what we do is we learn that life can get complicated,

58
00:02:41,735 --> 00:02:44,096
and schemas evolve and develop into more specific

59
00:02:44,256 --> 00:02:46,357
and hopefully more accurate mental representations.

60
00:02:46,717 --> 00:02:48,198
And this is referred to as accommodation.

61
00:02:48,858 --> 00:02:51,839
And it allows mental frameworks to adapt and progressively change

62
00:02:52,179 --> 00:02:55,861
from simple concepts to more complicated representational concepts.

63
00:02:56,638 --> 00:03:01,246
like this. So we learned that schemas or dogs in this case contain a bit of variety and

64
00:03:01,286 --> 00:03:05,213
our mental frameworks adapt. And by the way, we are doing this our entire lives. This is

65
00:03:05,273 --> 00:03:08,298
not just something that children go through as they learn and grow.

66
00:03:09,744 --> 00:03:13,148
experience invoke and change their schemas, so do artists and programmers,

67
00:03:13,648 --> 00:03:17,732
players do as well. Really nobody is immune. So in cognitive science what we

68
00:03:17,752 --> 00:03:22,457
do is we sort of work through schemas and activate them in different ways and

69
00:03:22,677 --> 00:03:25,881
one is through what's called conceptually driven schemas and this is

70
00:03:25,921 --> 00:03:27,182
known as top-down processing.

71
00:03:27,562 --> 00:03:31,085
So here we see Homer deliberately invoking his mental framework of bacon,

72
00:03:31,725 --> 00:03:34,507
which of course is delicious and I hope you're all not thinking about bacon

73
00:03:34,607 --> 00:03:37,850
and can instead stay with me here as I continue to talk about schemas

74
00:03:37,910 --> 00:03:38,891
and not talk about bacon.

75
00:03:39,451 --> 00:03:42,573
And strategy is another good example of this as well.

76
00:03:42,893 --> 00:03:46,636
So with top-down processing in a game, let's say like Rocket League,

77
00:03:47,699 --> 00:03:50,762
What happens is what's called endogenous thinking.

78
00:03:51,282 --> 00:03:53,144
And players learn strategy quickly.

79
00:03:53,665 --> 00:03:56,447
And they learn best practices and procedures

80
00:03:57,027 --> 00:03:59,450
to use these strategies, use this knowledge

81
00:03:59,510 --> 00:04:00,951
to inform how to play the game.

82
00:04:01,688 --> 00:04:05,949
For example, you should not really, in a game like Rocket League, send more than one teammate

83
00:04:06,249 --> 00:04:07,489
into the initial strike.

84
00:04:07,789 --> 00:04:13,030
You'll want to also maybe think about dividing the field and only watch the risk in terms

85
00:04:13,070 --> 00:04:13,910
of chasing the ball.

86
00:04:14,230 --> 00:04:16,591
Don't bunch up and keep the ball centered.

87
00:04:16,971 --> 00:04:18,771
Maybe if you're going for a more aggressive strategy.

88
00:04:19,731 --> 00:04:23,612
Personally, I find that the best offense is a good defense, and if you disagree with me,

89
00:04:24,092 --> 00:04:26,073
I look forward to meeting you in the arena.

90
00:04:27,500 --> 00:04:30,343
Gimas are also activated sometimes purely

91
00:04:30,423 --> 00:04:33,206
from a sensory level, or when the environment delivers

92
00:04:33,266 --> 00:04:34,648
a stimulus sort of at our feet.

93
00:04:35,248 --> 00:04:36,910
And this is more of a what's called

94
00:04:36,970 --> 00:04:38,692
data-driven type of processing.

95
00:04:39,173 --> 00:04:41,155
And here Homer is sort of minding his own business,

96
00:04:41,395 --> 00:04:43,617
and he happens upon the cola machine.

97
00:04:43,677 --> 00:04:45,239
He might not have been thinking about

98
00:04:45,719 --> 00:04:48,783
this attitude object before, but he definitely is now,

99
00:04:49,023 --> 00:04:50,745
and it may even change or alter his behavior.

100
00:04:51,397 --> 00:04:56,702
And for those in this room who have maybe experience playing Fortnite or other battle royale games,

101
00:04:57,082 --> 00:05:01,666
what tends to happen is sometimes the environment is so intense that player strategy just goes right out the window.

102
00:05:02,227 --> 00:05:03,548
I'm going to drop into this zone.

103
00:05:04,348 --> 00:05:05,970
No, there's 30 other players that are here.

104
00:05:06,070 --> 00:05:06,750
Now what do I do?

105
00:05:07,011 --> 00:05:07,671
Now where do I go?

106
00:05:08,232 --> 00:05:10,333
And here the environment is telling the player what's going on.

107
00:05:11,198 --> 00:05:14,882
And what they might get into is a little bit different

108
00:05:14,902 --> 00:05:16,123
than what they might have expected.

109
00:05:16,543 --> 00:05:18,265
And they need to prepare themselves for what's coming.

110
00:05:18,565 --> 00:05:20,587
So sometimes players have to adapt their strategy

111
00:05:20,647 --> 00:05:21,768
based on how the game is going.

112
00:05:22,129 --> 00:05:24,371
And schemas are what shoulder this burden for us.

113
00:05:24,591 --> 00:05:28,175
Schemas allow us to shift between top-down processing

114
00:05:28,515 --> 00:05:31,658
and bottom-up processing and meet the demands of the game.

115
00:05:31,898 --> 00:05:33,440
So mentally, there's an app for that

116
00:05:33,680 --> 00:05:34,641
and it's called a schema.

117
00:05:35,502 --> 00:05:38,724
So in other games and I'm using destiny here as an example.

118
00:05:39,345 --> 00:05:42,527
We oftentimes refer to on strategy-based schemas

119
00:05:42,827 --> 00:05:45,629
for planning and the more that you are aware of these schemas,

120
00:05:45,769 --> 00:05:47,591
the better you're going to play.

121
00:05:47,891 --> 00:05:50,393
But that doesn't mean that players won't also be interested

122
00:05:50,873 --> 00:05:52,634
if something does sort of pop up in front of them

123
00:05:52,674 --> 00:05:54,896
like a golden treasure chest or a loot crate.

124
00:05:55,396 --> 00:05:57,798
And there are things that will...

125
00:05:58,931 --> 00:06:04,556
inform the player that they're close at the environmental level. It could be a sound cue that they're getting close to something that might be

126
00:06:04,616 --> 00:06:12,523
interesting or worth checking out. So one question that I always pose to my students is, is it possible for

127
00:06:13,024 --> 00:06:19,990
schemas in terms of top-down and bottom-up processing to coexist and truly be simultaneous?

128
00:06:20,731 --> 00:06:23,774
And if we think about it, the answer is yes.

129
00:06:24,645 --> 00:06:25,326
It is possible.

130
00:06:25,806 --> 00:06:28,687
Knowing strategy and the schemas around that is a good thing.

131
00:06:29,527 --> 00:06:31,768
Being open to the demands of the environment

132
00:06:31,888 --> 00:06:33,908
and sort of knowing that we should react

133
00:06:34,028 --> 00:06:36,589
to what the game throws at us is also a good thing.

134
00:06:36,909 --> 00:06:38,430
So you may start with one strategy,

135
00:06:38,690 --> 00:06:40,050
the game throws something else at you,

136
00:06:40,370 --> 00:06:42,371
and schemas allow us to adapt and shift

137
00:06:42,411 --> 00:06:44,871
between these different types of combinations

138
00:06:44,911 --> 00:06:45,792
of mental processing.

139
00:06:46,632 --> 00:06:49,033
So, games are not only able to do this,

140
00:06:49,133 --> 00:06:50,873
they are notorious for doing this.

141
00:06:51,760 --> 00:06:54,023
In the case of what we have here, Robo Recall,

142
00:06:54,324 --> 00:06:55,585
there are plenty of game examples

143
00:06:55,625 --> 00:06:58,348
where devs absolutely throw a wrench in the plans

144
00:06:58,649 --> 00:07:00,831
of the best laid strategies that players have.

145
00:07:01,292 --> 00:07:02,533
The player understands where to go,

146
00:07:02,874 --> 00:07:05,957
the checkpoint is here, the game has informed them,

147
00:07:05,998 --> 00:07:09,682
it could be a narrator, a narration, it could be an NPC.

148
00:07:10,630 --> 00:07:12,431
and they already know where they have to go.

149
00:07:13,011 --> 00:07:15,893
Unfortunately, enemy agents arrive on the scene,

150
00:07:15,933 --> 00:07:17,314
they're probably blocking the path,

151
00:07:17,414 --> 00:07:20,035
and the player's forced to sort of accommodate

152
00:07:20,255 --> 00:07:23,057
and use that environmental input in a way moving forward.

153
00:07:23,457 --> 00:07:25,378
And this is schema accommodation.

154
00:07:25,599 --> 00:07:27,520
I have a plan, but the game world did something else.

155
00:07:28,380 --> 00:07:30,842
So this is one thing that I wanted to kind of highlight

156
00:07:30,862 --> 00:07:31,702
with this presentation.

157
00:07:31,842 --> 00:07:34,344
Another one is how do we predict

158
00:07:34,564 --> 00:07:35,885
what players are going to attend to?

159
00:07:36,740 --> 00:07:40,501
People are complicated, and so are their perceptions.

160
00:07:40,562 --> 00:07:42,963
But the good news is that science has repeatedly shown us

161
00:07:43,123 --> 00:07:44,483
that we can, to a large extent,

162
00:07:44,603 --> 00:07:47,205
predict certain aspects of human behavior.

163
00:07:47,625 --> 00:07:49,466
And one way is to invoke schemas

164
00:07:49,506 --> 00:07:50,946
that will guide information processing

165
00:07:51,067 --> 00:07:52,747
through what's called conceptual fluency.

166
00:07:53,388 --> 00:07:55,629
And in terms of understanding player perceptions

167
00:07:55,929 --> 00:07:57,870
and predicting those perceptions,

168
00:07:58,190 --> 00:07:59,951
conceptual fluency is one of those things

169
00:08:00,311 --> 00:08:02,492
that's all about invoking schema consistency.

170
00:08:03,312 --> 00:08:06,195
and designing game elements that rely sometimes pretty heavily

171
00:08:06,915 --> 00:08:10,038
on how to navigate the game world and wrestle with stimuli

172
00:08:10,479 --> 00:08:11,980
and adapt their strategies.

173
00:08:12,300 --> 00:08:14,562
So players have a long history, as you can see,

174
00:08:14,682 --> 00:08:17,765
with certain icons for schemas, and we build game icons

175
00:08:17,805 --> 00:08:19,426
around those perceptions that can

176
00:08:19,526 --> 00:08:21,608
and should be easily recognized.

177
00:08:22,008 --> 00:08:24,450
And when we do recognize them, what happens is it aligns

178
00:08:24,470 --> 00:08:27,493
with what we know and what we expect, and it's automatic.

179
00:08:27,793 --> 00:08:30,295
Information processing is easy, and it feels good.

180
00:08:31,076 --> 00:08:35,198
And really this is now sort of getting into the domain of UX versus UI,

181
00:08:35,238 --> 00:08:36,919
which I don't have time to talk about today.

182
00:08:37,259 --> 00:08:39,280
But I wanted to just sort of introduce this concept here,

183
00:08:39,641 --> 00:08:40,861
because we are going to circle back to it.

184
00:08:41,262 --> 00:08:44,703
So let's consider an example of how, let's say,

185
00:08:44,743 --> 00:08:47,705
a typical player would interact with something like a game menu.

186
00:08:48,385 --> 00:08:51,627
And the new game is generally listed at the top of the menu

187
00:08:51,707 --> 00:08:53,208
with exit at the bottom.

188
00:08:53,228 --> 00:08:56,170
And that's a schema that I think every single person in this room probably has.

189
00:08:57,154 --> 00:09:02,436
And when those puzzle pieces click together with what I know and what I experience, this

190
00:09:02,576 --> 00:09:04,337
generates conceptual fluency.

191
00:09:05,038 --> 00:09:09,359
Here is another example from the Witcher series and you can see again we have a relative match.

192
00:09:09,439 --> 00:09:13,201
That new game is listed at the top and exit or quit is at the bottom.

193
00:09:13,681 --> 00:09:15,562
Here is another example where

194
00:09:16,002 --> 00:09:16,903
things are aligning.

195
00:09:17,183 --> 00:09:19,424
And in all three instances, the mental rule is in place.

196
00:09:19,744 --> 00:09:21,525
And we have a schema match.

197
00:09:21,705 --> 00:09:24,806
Information processing is easy, everything is as expected,

198
00:09:25,166 --> 00:09:26,927
and cognitive load is relatively light.

199
00:09:27,467 --> 00:09:28,868
However, what sometimes happens

200
00:09:28,968 --> 00:09:30,829
is schemas don't always match to their environment.

201
00:09:31,547 --> 00:09:33,868
Here suddenly there is a mismatch with this rendering,

202
00:09:34,268 --> 00:09:37,250
and easy and automatic thinking is momentarily disrupted.

203
00:09:37,810 --> 00:09:39,631
And as the player is asked to accommodate

204
00:09:39,651 --> 00:09:40,651
to this new arrangement,

205
00:09:41,011 --> 00:09:43,092
that violates some of their prior expectancies.

206
00:09:43,153 --> 00:09:45,694
And cognitively we have to work just a little bit harder,

207
00:09:45,954 --> 00:09:46,474
just a little bit.

208
00:09:46,894 --> 00:09:50,376
This creates what psychologists call conceptual disfluency,

209
00:09:51,057 --> 00:09:53,298
and conceptual disfluency leads to something

210
00:09:53,538 --> 00:09:54,558
called attentional blink.

211
00:09:55,729 --> 00:09:58,891
So when schemas are violated, mentally we often have to pause.

212
00:09:59,311 --> 00:10:03,014
Orange juice and chocolate chip cookies is not in my wheelhouse.

213
00:10:03,054 --> 00:10:04,795
My students say, go on, you should just try it.

214
00:10:04,855 --> 00:10:05,555
I'm not having it.

215
00:10:05,595 --> 00:10:06,316
I'm not going to do it.

216
00:10:06,616 --> 00:10:07,577
It's too much for me.

217
00:10:08,117 --> 00:10:10,339
I don't have time to tell you what's wrong with this combination,

218
00:10:10,379 --> 00:10:11,379
but it's not a good one for me.

219
00:10:11,900 --> 00:10:16,643
And when the disfluency is too strong, what happens is we reject it.

220
00:10:17,284 --> 00:10:19,865
Here's another example of my students.

221
00:10:20,366 --> 00:10:22,267
They send me emails, and they say, just go for it.

222
00:10:22,407 --> 00:10:23,768
And again, I'm not having it.

223
00:10:24,924 --> 00:10:29,007
it's feel free to do as you see fit I don't want to hear about it. So with

224
00:10:29,067 --> 00:10:36,634
conceptual disfluency is another example again from my students this is something

225
00:10:36,734 --> 00:10:41,378
called Cage of Thrones which is just a Google click away and most of the major

226
00:10:41,418 --> 00:10:45,421
characters from Game of Thrones are photoshopped with the head of Nicolas

227
00:10:45,461 --> 00:10:46,082
Cage on instead.

228
00:10:46,977 --> 00:10:47,837
And to each their own.

229
00:10:48,237 --> 00:10:50,459
The thing about Cage of Thrones that's interesting is that

230
00:10:50,799 --> 00:10:53,340
Nicolas Cage doesn't really belong in Game of Thrones at all.

231
00:10:54,001 --> 00:10:57,063
And it creates a very profound attentional blink.

232
00:10:57,583 --> 00:11:01,305
And this, what's especially interesting is that these characters are so iconic

233
00:11:01,345 --> 00:11:03,867
that if you put your hand sort of over the head of this character,

234
00:11:03,907 --> 00:11:05,828
you could probably identify who it is.

235
00:11:06,368 --> 00:11:08,649
And audiences don't even need to see their faces.

236
00:11:09,350 --> 00:11:16,151
This hairstyle alone is enough of a cue to invoke a mental representation of a certain character,

237
00:11:16,691 --> 00:11:22,392
and we see Nicolas Cage's face instead. And by the way, to be clear, Cage of Thrones is an equal

238
00:11:22,432 --> 00:11:28,134
opportunity Photoshop endeavor, and no woman, man, or child who has a leading role in this series is

239
00:11:28,814 --> 00:11:33,355
particularly safe. I just happened to pick two characters here that are popular, and there are

240
00:11:33,415 --> 00:11:33,795
plenty more.

241
00:11:34,329 --> 00:11:37,851
And it's perfectly fine to laugh when there is conceptual disfluency,

242
00:11:37,891 --> 00:11:40,792
but the point to remember is that there's a schema violation,

243
00:11:41,272 --> 00:11:42,613
and we do recover from them.

244
00:11:43,273 --> 00:11:44,414
And they can be interesting,

245
00:11:44,854 --> 00:11:47,035
but what happens that I hope that you would focus on

246
00:11:47,115 --> 00:11:49,616
is that there's a shift from automatic processing

247
00:11:49,676 --> 00:11:52,157
to a more controlled type of cognitive processing.

248
00:11:52,765 --> 00:11:55,286
So getting back to games, as an example, oh I'm sorry,

